deck_excerpt: Hiro Mill OTK ft. Morphing Jar #2+Wattfox+Wanghu
deck_description:
Greetings! In this deck, we will mill the opponent with "Hiro's Shadow Scout" alongside series of combinations to not get interrupted by any means. Let's have a look.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Link Summon Saryuja when you have 4 cards in your Main Deck (MD) and shuffle back 3, all of which has to be spells. Then, Special Summon Hiro with Saryuja but only if you have up to 3 x MD monsters, including Hiro. Also, although not mandatory, place Baronne on Main Monster Zone (MMZ).

2) Clear at least 2 x MMZ with Ravenous/Baronne/Raigeki. Then, set all Traps and end your turn. During your opponent's Draw Phase, activate these Traps in order explained below:

  1. Powerful Rebirth >>> Wattfox
  2. Reverse Reuse >>> MJ #2 as face-down
  3. Give and Take >>> Wanghu
  4. All-Out Attacks

3) What is going to happen is that Wanghu destroys Wattfox, which shuts down anything your opponent can try to break you, including hand-traps. Then, via All-Out Attacks, MJ #2 will flip face-up and you can start milling your opponent. While your Traps are resolving, feel free to negate one thing your opponent can activate in response to them with Baronne.

4) After your job is done with Traps, MJ #2 is going to excavate three monsters, which are MJ #2 + Hiro + Wanghu. Should it come to that, place these monsters in order below and know that if you have two more Main Deck monsters, place them as last:

  1. MJ #2
  2. Hiro
  3. Wanghu

5) Now, your opponent draws 3 cards each time Hiro has been activated. So, repeat what was explained in #4 until your opponent is out of cards.

deck_excerpt: Be the reason someone quits master duel.
deck_description:
I want you to be aware that this deck is the problem. It is a condensed ball of every problem Yugioh boomers and other card game players will lie about on Twitter. Usually, this is just nonsense, but in our case, it is a guide. Run down the timer with your combos, throw out stupid staples, and make a million negates.

Be the reason someone quits master duel.

 

So here’s my modern-day deck list for 60 6 samurai. It’s very straightforward, you’re playing 3 of every six samurai monster that can spam out other six samurai monsters or special summon themselves for free. 3 Kizaru, 3 Grandmaster, 3 Great Shogun Shien, and 3 Kageki.

We’re also running 3 Mizuho and 3 Shinai. Each one of these special summons themself from their hand if you control the other. This matters since they’re searchable from secret Six Samurai Kizaru. Even more so since this deck’s best 2 extenders are rank 3.

This gets us into a larger point of strategy. Counter generation. Six Samurai as a deck revolve around generating bushido counters every time a Six Samurai monster is summoned. Gateway of the Six Samurai let’s us search for a Six Samurai monster for every 4 counters anywhere. But it only generates 2 counters for each summon. This means we either need multiple counter-generating cards or we can use extenders to turn every 2 monsters into a different 2 monsters and some counters.

For example. 2 levels 3’s go into M-X Saber invoker which goes into kizaru and a search. Or islolde into hatsune. Going two for 2.5 lets the deck deal with heavy costs and negs that come with link spamming and starting combos.

I’ll also mention here the three great shogun shien. It’s a hard floodgate of an opponent’s spells and traps that summons itself for free. In the TCG I’d be a bit more hesitant about running it, but in Master Duel's janky best-of-one format it’s so much stronger than it has any right to be.

This list makes use of several powerful engines. Most notable is the Kashtira engine. It’s a simple tool that gets us disruption removal and free attack thanks to the field spell.

But even more interesting is the zodiac engine. Zodiac Barrage has no restrictions or real cost so At its most basic it pulls out an extra material for a link monster or just an extra disruption with Zoodiac Drident. But more interestingly we can use zodiac barrage to destroy six samurai fuma to trigger her effect.  So it ends up being a plus one. Fuma is also searchable thanks to Isolde two tales of the noble knights or literally any six samurai searcher.

Zodiac Barrage and Kashtiras contribute to what put this deck head and shoulders above my early iterations. Not only is it a stupid wombo combo deck, but you have tools to play going second.

 

The extra deck is very straightforward. Let’s split it into extenders and end board.

We have the before-mentioned extenders of mx saber invoker and Isolde but let me explain the other 3. Battle Shogun of the Six Samurai is a searcher for Gateway of the Six Samurai. He does take as discard and doesn’t lead to any further plays on his own so he has to be used either in specific 3-4 card combos or after we’ve done some setup with Isolde and M-X Saber Invoker. Basically, unless you're guaranteed to have follow up don’t make him.

Skull Dread Saryuja is a bread and butter extender. Especially since most of this deck is extenders and 1-card engines. Drawing 4 is crazy and with some extra searches, thanks to Isolde, Gateway and Kizaru the put-back 3 cost doesn’t hurt.

Leviar is an extender’s extender. If we have already used mx saber invoker and Isolde to make Hatsume we can then follow up the hatsume skill with a leviair. To keep the loops going. It’s very overkill, but does sustain some otherwise suboptimal starts.

For our end boards, we have a large chunk dedicated to generic link spam. IP Masquerna lets us benefit from leaving out materials. Knightmare Gryphon is a monster effect negate floodgate. Appollosa is just 4 monster negates. And Underworld Goddess is a out to problematic monsters and an extra target for I:P.

For XYZ’s we have Abyss Dweller and Bagooska. Bagooska is a simple backup plan. Abyss Dweller is an anti-graveyard floodgate. Master Duel being a best-of-one format makes this awkward to use. Since you kinda just gotta feel it.

Naturia Beast and six samurai shien are our spell negates. Of course, Naturia Beast is a much better play but we need access to Shien’s Squire to get it. This means we have to go through a limited number of good but not guaranteed options to get it from the deck. Much more often we’ll go for shi en who’s only 1 spell or trap negate.

Gameplan

1) At one point, send Number 13 to GY and bring forth Smashtank.

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to setup a "Primal Seed" loop. Just don't banish Number 13 by accident and you will be fine.

3) Revive Number 13 with "Monster Reborn" and overlay into Number 43 with "Rank-Up-Magic Launch".

4) Fetch all cards from Banish Zone (BZ) to your hand with "Primal Seed" and activate Smashtank to discard all but "Mystik Wok" to boost its ATK.

5) With Smashtank having huge amount of ATK points, activate "Mystik Wok" to target Smashtank and choose its ATK. The amount you gained as LP can be reflected as damage to your opponent thanks to Number 43.

6) Congratulations, you win the game!

deck_excerpt: cute n smol runick-powered melffys + tri-brigade support
deck_description:
Melffys are cute as fuck but dead serious when it comes to be a major annoyance for your opponent.

Runick Fountain and Melffy Hide-and-Seek makes for a great drawing / recycling engine.

Hugin the Runick Wings searches for Runick Fountain and can be used as a rk.2 xyz or synchro material.

The Runick engine combined with the melffy engine allows you to respond to each of your opponent's actionduring their turn. Melffy Wally can bring Melffy Catty and Melffy Puppy out. Then they can bring Melffy Pinny or Hop Ear Squadron to your hand and summon a beast to your field like Tri-Brigade Kitt, which can lead to the synchro summon of Merry Melffys or Desert Locusts, which can itself be used to summon Borreload Dragon or Baronne de Fleur, all of that during your opponent's turn! Melffy of the Forest and each of your Runick spells can further block your opponent and destroy their cards.

Tri-Brigade Shuraig the Ominous Omen works wonderfully with the melffy engine, allowing you to banish a card on the field (without targetting) each single turn as you summon out your smol creatures. Rescue Cat summons out Tri-Brigade Kitt and Melffy Pinny (or any other lv 2 beast), which can be used to summon Tri-Brigade Ferrijit the Barren Blossom. Tri-Brigade Kitt sends Tri-Brigade Nervall to the grave, which adds Tri-Brigade Kerass to your hand. Summon the bad boy, get another link2 monster out and then Shuraig can come out.

In a nutshell: this deck can go crazy! Try it!

It's times like these when I realize how much I am blinded by the presence of World Legacy Monstrosity at times. Today's Level 9 monster we are taking a look at is Deskbot 009 which is a Level 9 EARTH Machine monster whereas its effect could matter less. I should've come to realization of what a Deskbot Prediction Princess Deck should be much sooner, but at the time, I was thinking "Deskbot 009 is an EARTH monster, this is not going to work," like a dumbdumb and I completely forgot that Machine Duplication exists. You see, every Deskbot monster has 500 ATK/DEF and they each have their own ways of increasing their ATK/DEF to very large amounts. They are practically begging you to use Machine Duplication with them. And the Deskbot cards actually make getting to 009 extremely easy, specifically Deskbot 003 does. On Normal Summon, 003 can Special Summon a Deskbot monster from Deck, except for itself, which can immediately get a 009 onto the field. There you go. End of story. Now just activate Machine Duplication for 2 more copies of 009 from Deck, and now you've got yourself Rank 9 access and an additional Level 9 monster to boot. So all you really need for combo is Deskbot 003 and Machine Duplication. Now, we are playing Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag and 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which we can use for Bibliomuse access through Summoning Kaku for free (by Linking 003 into Salamangreat Almiraj), but we don't exactly need to rely on it. And if we don't draw Monstrosity or Machine Dupe, we can just use 009 and Kaku as Rank 9 access. You could instead play a Pre-Preparation of Rites package with Prediction Ritual but I like Bibliomuse access more. 

For the monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei is a Quick Effect to flip a monster face-up or face-down and during the End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. On flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from GY face-down if she was tributed and sent there. On flip, she can add a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while she’s face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. For our Flips, we have 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck. 3 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag which can Special Summoned from hand if there is a monster in the Extra Monster Zone. This is extremely easy to do in this Deck with you being able to Link off a Normal Summoned Diviner of the Herald or Deskbot 003 for a Salamangreat Almiraj. Also, you can target a face-up monster in the EMZ and equip it and when this card destroys a monster by battle, you can Special Summon a monster card that is equipped to it. Kaku is good for just getting a Level 9 onto the field, but it can also act as removal in some applications as well. And on top of both of those things, it makes for a good Small World bridge due to its Type and Attribute. 3 Deskbot 009 and 3 Deskbot 003. 009 is just a Level 9 monster that we can easily access through 003 and Machine Dupe. 003 can Special Summon a Deskbot straight from Deck on Normal Summon. Both have 500 ATK which means that they can both be targeted by Machine Duplication and because Machine Dupe is not a once per turn, if you draw more than one, you can dupe 009 first for Rank 9 plays and then dupe 003 for Link plays. 3 Diviner of the Herald which sends a Fairy from Deck or Extra Deck to GY to increase its Level by the Level of the sent monster. And because it has 500 ATK and is a LIGHT Fairy, it makes as a good way to bridge to 003. And finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. 

Spell/Traps: 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can also banish it from GY during the Standby Phase in order to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 3 Small World. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 from hand or target a Level 9 you control and Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from Deck with a different Type and Attribute than it but with different names. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Machine Duplication which targets a Machine monster you control with 500 or less ATK and Special Summons up to 2 monsters from Deck with the same name as that monster. And finally, 3 Pot of Prosperity. 

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator which sends a monster from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon and can target monsters in your GY up to the number of its materials, detach the same number of materials, and attach those monsters in GY to itself as material. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Underworld Goddess of the Underworld. 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Gravity Controller and 1 Salamangreat Almiraj. 

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 1 Kurikara Divincarnate, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Harpie's Feather Duster, 3 Infinite Impermanence, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: So Isolde got banned, now what? Let's do this.
deck_description:
Intro

Isolde got banned in the most recent Forbidden/Limited list so this deck got a massive hit. All warrior extenders are not useful now because in order to do the same combo as before we now need 2 Goukis instead of 2 Warriors. So let's look at the current combos:

Combos

[Combo #1]: 1 Suprex + 1 other Gouki (not Headbatt)

  1. Normal Summon Gouki Suprex > effect to Special Summon other Gouki (ex. Gouki Twistcobra)
  2. Link Summon Gouki Jet Ogre > Goukis' effects in GY to add Gouki Headbatt and another Gouki (ex. Gouki Riscorpio)
  3. Headbatt effect to Special Summon it discarting Riscorpio.
  4. Link Summon Gouki Thunder Ogre > Headbatt effect to add another Gouki (ex. Gouki Iron Claw)
  5. Extra Normal Summon Iron Claw.
  6. Link Summon Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess > Iron Claw effect to add Gouki Re-Match.
  7. Activate Re-Match special summoning Riscorpio and another Gouki.
  8. Link Summon Codebreaker Virus Swordsman > effect to Special Summon Codebreaker Zero Day and Riscorpio effect to add Re-Match.
  9. Link Summon Codebreaker Virus Berserker > effect to Special Summon back the Virus Swordsman and Zero Day.
  10. Link Summon them into The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche to the right zone.
  11. Bardiche effect sending The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots to GY and setting The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine.
  12. Activate Brigandine summoning itself as a monster.
  13. Link Summon Gouki The Powerload Ogre with Berserker and Brigandine.
  14. Silent Boots effect in GY banishing itself to add Phantom Knights' Fog Blade, set it and End Turn.

End Board: 3 monster negates (2 from Apollousa and 1 from Fog Blade) and 1 unaffected monster (Powerload)

Note: In step 11 you can set 1 other Fog Blade instead of the Brigandine to end with 4 monster negates.

[Combo #2]: 1 Headbatt + 2 other different Goukis

  1. Normal Summon a Gouki (ex. Riscorpio)
  2. Headbatt effect to Special Summon it discarting another Gouki (ex. Twistcobra)
  3. Link Summon Jet Ogre > Goukis' effects in GY to add Re-Match and Suprex.
  4. Activate Re-Match special summoning Twistcobra and another Gouki.
  5. Link Summon Thunder Ogre using Jet Ogre and Twistcobra > Twistcobra effect to add another Gouki (ex. Iron Claw)
  6. Extra Normal Summon Suprex > effect to Special Summon Iron Claw.
  7. Link Summon Apollousa using Thunder Ogre and Iron Claw > Iron Claw effect to add Re-Match.
  8. [Continue with step 8 from Combo #1]

[Combo #3]: Going Second OTK

  1. Normal Summon Suprex > effect to Special Summon Twistcobra.
  2. Link Summon Jet Ogre > Goukis' effects in GY to add Headbatt and another Gouki (ex. Riscorpio)
  3. Headbatt effect to Special Summon it discarting Riscorpio.
  4. Link Summon Thunder Ogre > Headbatt effect to add Re-Match.
  5. Activate Re-Match special summoning Riscorpio and Twistcobra.
  6. Link Summon Gouki The Master Ogre > Riscorpio effect to add Gouki Finishing Move.
  7. Activate Finishing Move.
  8. Go to Battle Phase.
  9. Attack with Master Ogre > on Damage Step activate Twistcobra's effect to tribute itself to give more ATK to Master Ogre.

8400 battle damage.

[Combo #4]: Bricking

  1. Set a Gouki and Torrential Tribute.
  2. End Phase.
  3. Add Suprex when the set Gouki gets destroyed.

Yep.

deck_excerpt: I'm holding out for a HERO!
deck_description: Deck is as competative of a deck as I could theorycraft. I'm a huge fan of heroes and this is my attempt to bring my spin on a deck that could stand a chance against these newer decks
Just cyber dragons
Ib the World Chalice Justiciar + World Legacy - "World Chalice" can summon Baronne de Fleur. Auram the World Chalice Blademaster + Link Spider can summon Decode Talker Heatsoul.
Playable witchcrafter deck. May be tier 2 or lower but have a chance to win :)

One-Card Starters:

(9) Herald (Spell Negate) + Laevateinn + Trias in GY + Boss Stage:

3x Wakaushi

3x Bike -> Wakaushi

3x Wagon -> Gigant X -> Wakaushi (Note: Any way to Gigant X is Full-Combo)

(17) Ways to get to Boss Stage:

3x Wakaushi, 3x Bike, 3x Wagon, 3x Loptyr, 1x Planet Pathfinder, 1x Terraforming, 3x Boss Stage

Strengths:

Almost without fail, if left uninterrupted you get to go full combo without a hitch. Typically if you don't full-combo, it's because you already drew what you were searching and just opened boss stage + monstrosity anyways. There are also a lot of two-card combos that get you to the ideal board even if you don’t draw any starters, but in most cases you’re working with one-card combos that use additional cards as extension to play through hand traps.

An issue this deck had previously was drawing a Generaider you wanted to summon off of Boss Stage. No more, Lee allows you to trade any monster in your hand for itself, which turns a brick into a negate so long as Herald of Mirage Lights is on the field. Summon Vala off of Boss Stage, et voila. 

One also might be concerned about mixing Spells with Superheavy, but this deck actually has a good answer for that. When summoning Jormungandr using Laevateinn, you can equip any spells from grave that might dead a Superheavy on a future turn if it looks like you might have to go for a second round of combo.

The Superheavies also give you access to a Pendulum Summon - Regrettably only at a maximum scale of 8, but that’s more than enough to Pend extra superheavies, Lee, or Loptyr. 

Weaknesses & Deck Building Concessions:

There's a really good argument to play 1 Superheavy Samurai Scales and a decent argument to play 1 Superheavy Samurai Security, as they can sometimes help you play through hand traps. That's the main reason Soulgaia Booster and Soulpiercer were bumped to three, and Vala cut to 1. I didn’t feel comfortable including them due to how many garnets this deck already has, but they do have their own merit. I even spent time testing Superheavy Samurai Magnet as a way to increase the amount of two-card combos and as a way to bait/play through interruption, but at least in my testing, it didn’t result in any meaningful/guaranteed additional lines.

I didn't feel good about it, but I cut the Ty-Phon for Baronne & Assault Synchro Stardust Dragon. Cutting Crocodragon Archethys didn't feel bad; Typically if you're able to make it you're already winning anyways. If you get hand trapped once or twice, if you can't force through to Ib & Monstrosity you can usually at least end on Baronne. You might cut Trencher for Ty-Phon, but I’m not familiar enough with Generaider to make that call.

If your opponent holds the Ash for Monstrosity, you're screwed... Unless you can weave in Gigant X for Pathfinder before summoning Trishula, in which case you can just pend it out. You at least still get to Boss Stage in this scenario, and I liked having a secondary way to bridge the Superheavies to the Generaiders. If you open Pathfinder, just think of it as bad Loptyr.

The Ib and Soulpiercer searches are typically chainblocked by Wakaushi effect to scale itself and Tilting effect to summon Wakaushi from the extra respectively.

A hand trap on Titling/Gigant X typically hurts as well, though sometimes it just doesn't matter and you can play through it either by setting up an additional Superheavy body or by using it to bait interaction when you already have another way to Wakaushi. Same goes for an Ash on specifically Big Benkei. However, all of these spots are risky to hand trap since certain extenders let you play through them unscathed; The conundrum is kind of like pre-banlist R-ACE.

I tried really hard to make a version of the combo where you summon Baronne before triggering Monstrosity, but I seriously struggled to make both happen. You’re usually missing a tuner.

I cut the Diviner lines because most of the time, you'd rather have a Special summon as opposed to a 2nd or 3rd normal summon stuck in your hand. It also allows you to cut Nidhogg, since you no longer have to worry about activating Monstrosity on Trias Hierarchia.

Conclusion:

You’re still playing Generaider. You still have the potential to lose to every hand trap under the sun, but at least this build can sometimes play through them. However, the heightened ceiling that the guaranteed access to Monstrosity provides (via Ib) is ludicrous. If you pull off the combo, you’ve pretty much won the game on the spot. I struggle to imagine a deck that can break this board consistently without cards like Lava Golem or Sphere Mode.
I use this deck when I am crazy.

deck_name: Dragon Ruler deck,Ib the World Chalice Justiciar,Snatch Steal, post banlist 2024

deck_excerpt: Deck divertido y potente basado en el arquetipo Mundo Oscuro y ¡Peligro!
deck_description:
Deck ideal para salir de primer turno.

La idea es invocar cuanto antes a Ceruli, Guru of Dark World en el Campo del rival, teniendo a Sillva, Warlord of Dark World en la Mano, para descartar esta segunda carta al Cementerio y activar su efecto, que quita cartas de la Mano del adversario.

Genta, Gateman of Dark World es clave para traer la Mágica de Campo, la cual permite: desterrar, normalmente a Genta, que se invoca de forma especial; descartar, para activar efectos en el Cementerio de nuestros monstruos y robar.

Los monstruos Danger! Bigfoot!, Danger! Thunderbird!, Danger! Chupacabra!, Danger! Mothman!, Danger! Nessie!, Danger!? Tsuchinoko? y Danger!? Jackalope? permiten agilizar el Deck e invocarse a sí mismos de modo especial (robando, además, una carta) o activar sus efectos en el Cementerio para destruir cartas (principalmente). 

Nibiru, the Primal Being y Radian, the Multidimensional Kaiju permiten tributar Monstruos del rival e interrumpirle combos y posiciones de Monstruo en su campo. Pueden ser sustituidos por Lava Golem (en el Side Deck) para, además, infligirle 1000 LP de daño en su Standby Phase.

El Deck Extra posee monstruos con gran ataque y dificiles de matar, como Number 22: Zombiestein. Además, cuenta con el combo Number 97: Draglubion - Number 100: Numeron Dragon y la Fusión de Grapha, Dragon Overlord of Dark World que permite cambiar el efecto de una Mágica, Trampa o Monstruo del rival para descartarnos una carta y seguir moviendo el Deck.

Skill Drain es bastante útil contra Decks que se basan en activar efectos de Monstruos sobre el Campo. ¡OJO! Puede ser activado, solamente, durante la Standby Phase o cuando tu adversario active un efecto de Monstruo sobre el Campo y, además, también te afecta a ti.
spellcaster control 2

This is a simple more pure Dogmatika. It has many starters allowing you to get things going.

Ash can even be used as a starter to link into Almiraj and then Gardna. I love Iblee lock and honestly, it gets me a scoop more often than not, and if not doing the combo to rip more than half of their extra deck gets me the scoop. One huge weakness is people with little or no extra deck usage so I added a branded twist to the deck to balance this allowing for big extra deck monsters to also be summoned. There is also the ability to summon Luluwalilith with using her as either a target with Maximus if you see no way to get Alba Zoa or if you are able to summon Alba Zoa summoning Cartesia at the end of the turn. Use her effect only when your opponent uses a monster effect to summon a monster (Thing Magician Souls or Mathtech) allowing you to summon Grang in the chain, then when the monster is summoned you can use both his effects using the first to send him to the GY then using the 2nd effect to summon Luluwalilith.

While this deck does have flaws and is in no way Meta, you can still climb high and to be honest I use it as I love it. The changes you could make is one less Dogmatikalamity for another thrust or swap Iblee for Maxx c and while it pains me to say this White Relic & White Knight see very veryyyyy little play but are good when you find that perfect slot. I may experiment with taking Knight out but for now, I like this deck as it is. I do see people question Ashiyan but I find he works very well allowing me to get something I may need back from the GY.

deck_excerpt: Magic Crusher FTK ft. Primal Seed
deck_description:
Greetings! This is a basic deck to burn your opponent and I would like to show you how.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to setup a "Primal Seed" loop...

  • If you don't have ME-PSY-YA because it's UR card, you can instead Special Summon "Banisher of the Light" (R) with Saryuja, seen in "Side Deck".

2) Play Temple >>> Magic Crusher combo. Now, you can discard a spell to deal 500 damage. Repeat until your opponent is dead and don't forget to fetch spells from Banish Zone (BZ) with "Primal Seed" to continue as usual.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Type Zero Magic Crusher" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 90 SR and 60 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Temple of the Kings" can be found within "Guardian of Kings" Secret Pack to save 30 SR! As of this writing, you can also find this card in "The Ones Who Serve Ra" Timed Pack.

 

So, in total, you can save up to 630 SR and 120 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Natural Disaster FTK ft. The Dark Magicians
deck_description:
Welcome! In this deck, we will FTK with "Natural Disaster" thanks to assistance coming from "The Dark Magicians". Let me explain.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place Librarian on Main Monster Zone (MMZ) and discard Cirrostratus with Ravenous/Dugares.

2) When you have 4 cards in Main Deck, Link Summon Saryuja but don't use Librarian as material. Then, shuffle back all three "Natural Disaster" cards. After placing ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summoning Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to setup Primal Seed loop, Special Summon Parasite with Saryuja. This enables you to Fusion Summon "The Dark Magicians".

3) Play "The Humble Sentry" to shuffle "Give and Take" and activate Magicians to draw a Trap and set it.

4) Play "De-Fusion" to reset Magicians, which lets you draw rest of your Traps. When you have all Traps ready to go, activate "Give and Take" at first and then all "Natural Disaster" cards at last. If you have done everything right, each time Cirrostratus pops, you will deal 500 x 3 = 1500 damage in total.

5) In order to repeat what was explained in #4, you have to do what was told in #3 to win the game.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "The Dark Magicians" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 30 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Fusion Parasite" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 90 SR and 60 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Baronne de Fleur" can be found within "The Noble Knights of Crimson Flowers" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 180 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: At least the cards look cool...
deck_description: Eepy fr fr
sdfghj

Once again in my never-ending crusade to make my favorite archetypes cook in ways I never thought possible, I have found the best way to play Gameciel Turbo! Now, the concept of this deck is simple, go into Gameciel with Kyoutou Waterfront and bully our opponent with well-timed non one per turn omni-negates. However, because Konami won't give Kaijus any new support (hopefully for now), our best shot of playing Kyoutou are opening it, Terraforming, or Ancient Fairy Dragon and because Kaijus are limited by their own summon clause, Saryuja Skull Dread is our best friend.

 

Now what deck can link climb, synchro summon, AND search Kyoutou? Why Crusadia, of course! With two card combos that can end on two Link 4s, this deck has the sauce to get the job done. And of course, because it's me, I got a nice, little tech that gasses up the deck surprisingly well. The honorary Crusadia monsters Parallel eXceed and Link Infra-Flier are perfect for the deck and searchable with Cynet Mining for the latter, giving the deck functionally 7-8 more Crusadia monsters to extend with (depending on personal ratios), which means tehnically one Crusadia name is full combo with one of those cards.

 

The deck isn't the best, of course. The right number of negates can shut it down and that stupid rock is a thorn in its side, but if it can pop-off, it's a threat to behold. Not to mention it cheap, so you could cook it up for a relatively low price. What Kaijus you use outside of Gameciel (if any at all) is up to you all.
